But let's double-check: `testTypeAnnotations`:
```java
public void testTypeAnnotations() {
    test("x;", e);
    test("a.b.c.d;", e);
    test(" a.b.c.d;", ok);
    test("if (true) {  a.b.c.d; }", ok);

    test("function A() { this.foo; }", e);
    test("function A() {  this.foo; }", ok);
}
```
The last two lines: the first expects a warning (e) because `this.foo;` is a type parse error (using `this` outside a constructor). The second, with a space before `this.foo`, is considered to have a JSDoc annotation that suppresses the warning. This is exactly what the parser type warning controls. With the bug, if `checkTypes` is false (default), the parser type warning is turned off, so both would produce no warning, causing the first to get `ok` instead of `e`, failing. So yes.

`testJSDocComments`:
```java
public void testJSDocComments() {
    test("function A() {  this.foo; }", ok);
    test("function A() {  this.foo; }", e);
}
```
Similar.

